1
00:00:49,240 --> 00:00:53,080
Chris, what is it?

2
00:00:54,200 --> 00:00:58,000
I love you so much.

3
00:00:59,360 --> 00:01:02,440
Don't you love me any more?

4
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:18,160
I've made progress,
and I recognise that.

5
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:24,000
But my wife, who I can't
even convince to come here...

6
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:27,800
Anything can set her off.
It could be the phone ringing,

7
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:32,000
something on the news,
something online, going shopping maybe.

8
00:01:32,240 --> 00:01:36,720
A commemorative T-shirt in the window.
It just puts her right back in that place,

9
00:01:36,960 --> 00:01:41,880
and it's like all my progress - ripped away.
And I'm right back there with her.

10
00:01:42,120 --> 00:01:47,200
I feel totally the opposite. I see the TV
and I see the Internet and I see those T-shirts

11
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:53,440
and I feel nothing. The more I see the images,
the less I feel, the less I believe that it's real.

12
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:59,680
I mean, I think I'm supposed to feel
something by now. Don't you think so?

13
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:05,080
Linda, this is Chris Kelvin.
I'm returning your call.

14
00:02:05,320 --> 00:02:08,240
I have two times available this week;

15
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:13,280
7am on Tuesday
or 6.15pm on Thursday.

16
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:20,040
You can leave a message if either
of those times are good for you. Thank you.

17
00:02:20,280 --> 00:02:22,840
Well, I know that's not true.

18
00:02:23,080 --> 00:02:27,760
Because I know you, and I know it's not true.

19
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:34,600
Good. I'm glad.

20
00:02:34,840 --> 00:02:36,480
All right.

21
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:40,680
Let's pick this up on Wednesday.

22
00:03:41,920 --> 00:03:44,360
Can I help you?

23
00:03:44,600 --> 00:03:48,880
<i>We're looking for Dr Chris Kelvin.</i>

24
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:55,920
<i>Chris...</i>

25
00:03:57,160 --> 00:04:01,920
<i>I can't imagine what you must be
thinking, getting a message like this.</i>

26
00:04:02,160 --> 00:04:08,880
<i>I apologise if it seems melodramatic, but
you are the only person I can... I can trust...</i>

27
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:12,360
<i>in the situation.</i>

28
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:15,000
<i>I need your help.</i>

29
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:17,760
<i>I need you to come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

30
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,800
<i>I don't know how to describe
what we are experiencing up here.</i>

31
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:27,280
<i>We can't even agree amongst ourselves
what is... what is happening, or...</i>

32
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:31,280
<i>what to do about it.</i>

33
00:04:31,800 --> 00:04:37,880
<i>I suppose the... the most obvious
solution would be to leave.</i>

34
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:44,720
<i>But none of us want to. That's why
you're getting this... this bizarre request.</i>

35
00:04:44,960 --> 00:04:47,760
<i>I...</i>

36
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,800
<i>I told the crew that your
background and experiences</i>

37
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:57,080
<i>made you the...
the ideal candidate for this job.</i>

38
00:04:57,320 --> 00:04:59,520
<i>Don't worry. I didn't elaborate.</i>

39
00:05:01,280 --> 00:05:03,960
<i>But it's true.</i>

40
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:07,680
<i>So, anyway...</i>

41
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:12,440
<i>I, uh... I hope you will come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

42
00:05:12,680 --> 00:05:15,280
<i>L- I think you need to.</i>

43
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:18,680
<i>You will see what I mean.</i>

44
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:25,000
<i>I wish I could be more specific
about all of this, but... you know.</i>

45
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:29,280
<i>People are listening.</i>

46
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:38,800
You can imagine the distress
Dr Gibarian's message caused at DBA.

47
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:43,200
Why not send in the security force?

48
00:05:43,440 --> 00:05:47,880
We did. We lost contact
as they were approaching Solaris.

49
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:51,600
They haven't returned.

50
00:05:51,840 --> 00:05:54,600
There must be some
sort of on-board Al system.

51
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:56,640
They shut it down.

52
00:05:56,880 --> 00:06:01,000
The company was hoping to solve
this problem without involving a civilian.

53
00:06:01,240 --> 00:06:05,560
Obviously these are extreme circumstances.

54
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:09,400
Some preparation is involved
but you shouldn't have any trouble.

55
00:06:09,640 --> 00:06:15,920
The flight itself is fully automated.
You'll be asleep most of the trip.

56
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:23,840
We feel confident that if you board
the ship, you can negotiate their safe return.

57
00:06:24,080 --> 00:06:27,440
Is that what everybody wants?

58
00:06:27,680 --> 00:06:31,160
Of course.

59
00:11:43,680 --> 00:11:47,520
Find the probability of F.

60
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:53,880
OK, stop. Go back.

61
00:11:55,440 --> 00:11:58,920
Snow.

62
00:12:16,760 --> 00:12:19,960
Kelvin, is it?

63
00:12:20,200 --> 00:12:21,880
Yeah.

64
00:12:22,120 --> 00:12:25,840
Kelvin. Right. Oh, man.

65
00:12:26,080 --> 00:12:28,360
Sorry about that, Kelvin.

66
00:12:28,600 --> 00:12:30,600
Names, you know, just...

67
00:12:30,840 --> 00:12:32,960
For some reason. It, uh...

68
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:35,600
Yeah. Uh...

69
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:38,880
Well, uh, you wanna come in?

70
00:12:39,120 --> 00:12:41,200
I'm fine.

71
00:12:41,440 --> 00:12:46,360
Whose blood is that, leading to the lab?

72
00:12:46,520 --> 00:12:50,000
Yeah. Blood.

73
00:12:50,040 --> 00:12:53,480
How 'bout that?

74
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:58,400
Katarn.

75
00:12:58,640 --> 00:13:00,520
He, um... Yeah.

76
00:13:00,760 --> 00:13:05,680
Security forces showed up
and he just took off, and they...

77
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:09,160
Yeah. Put a hole in his pot.

78
00:13:09,400 --> 00:13:13,160
What happened to Gibarian?

79
00:13:14,280 --> 00:13:16,120
Yeah.

80
00:13:16,360 --> 00:13:20,160
It was a suicide.

81
00:13:21,160 --> 00:13:22,880
Who found him?

82
00:13:23,120 --> 00:13:26,040
I found him.

83
00:13:26,280 --> 00:13:29,400
What happened to Rhys?

84
00:13:29,640 --> 00:13:32,120
Yeah, now, Rhys w... Huh.

85
00:13:32,360 --> 00:13:36,440
We don't know, because the thing is,
he kind of... disappeared.

86
00:13:36,680 --> 00:13:38,440
- Disappeared?
- Disappeared.

87
00:13:38,680 --> 00:13:43,160
- How did he disappear?
- Exactly.

88
00:13:43,600 --> 00:13:46,720
Don't know. We do know
that he's not on the ship, uh,

89
00:13:46,960 --> 00:13:51,120
and that's... that's all we know.

90
00:13:51,360 --> 00:13:53,720
Where's Dr Gordon?

91
00:13:53,960 --> 00:13:57,440
Dr Gordon. She is in her room,

92
00:13:57,680 --> 00:13:59,360
and, um...

93
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:03,880
Dr Gordon won't let you in her room.

94
00:14:07,960 --> 00:14:12,440
Can you tell me what's happening here?

95
00:14:12,960 --> 00:14:15,240
I could tell you what's happening,

96
00:14:15,480 --> 00:14:18,120
but, uh...

97
00:14:18,360 --> 00:14:23,880
I don't know if that'd
really tell you what's happening.

98
00:14:29,560 --> 00:14:32,560
I just wanna talk to you.

99
00:14:32,800 --> 00:14:38,280
You have to give me your word
you won't try to come in.

100
00:14:41,120 --> 00:14:44,600
All right.

101
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,160
Well?

102
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:04,120
- What happened to Gibarian?
- Didn't you talk to Snow?

103
00:15:04,360 --> 00:15:07,640
- I wanted to hear your version.
- There isn't any version.

104
00:15:07,880 --> 00:15:11,640
He killed himself.

105
00:15:12,360 --> 00:15:17,480
Why haven't you come home?
What happened here?

106
00:15:17,640 --> 00:15:21,600
What did you find?

107
00:15:21,760 --> 00:15:25,640
- Who are you representing?
- I'm the last effort to recover this mission,

108
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:30,560
before they abandon this ship
and everyone on board.

109
00:15:38,840 --> 00:15:43,160
Until it starts happening to you,
there's really no point in discussing it.

110
00:16:05,840 --> 00:16:09,120
Hey.

111
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:18,360
Hey!

112
00:16:32,520 --> 00:16:36,080
<i>- Who else is here?
- Who else is here?</i>

113
00:16:36,320 --> 00:16:39,800
<i>I saw a boy.</i>

114
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:46,520
Gibarian's son.

115
00:16:46,920 --> 00:16:51,200
- Michael.
- How is that possible?

116
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:54,480
I think that's why you're here.

117
00:16:54,720 --> 00:16:58,320
I want a formal interview with you
and Gordon. I'll need your help with her.

118
00:16:58,560 --> 00:17:00,920
Yeah. All right.

119
00:17:01,160 --> 00:17:02,200
Um...

120
00:17:02,440 --> 00:17:04,680
How much sleep do you need, Kelvin?

121
00:17:04,920 --> 00:17:07,320
- How much sleep?
- Yeah.

122
00:17:07,560 --> 00:17:12,240
- How long can you go without sleep?
- Depends.

123
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:14,360
Well,

124
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:17,840
when you do go to sleep,

125
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:23,040
I find I sleep much better
with the door locked.

126
00:17:25,320 --> 00:17:30,880
<i>I was with the project when it was
still with NASA, before it was sold to DBA.</i>

127
00:17:31,120 --> 00:17:33,080
I was trained in physics.

128
00:17:33,320 --> 00:17:37,760
I was sent here to assess
the economic potential of Solaris.

129
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,640
Whether or not it was a viable commercial
property or possible energy source.

130
00:17:43,880 --> 00:17:47,960
I was still compiling data
when this shit started happening.

131
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:50,880
Did you run any tests
on the food, air, water?

132
00:17:51,120 --> 00:17:57,720
I checked it 50 times. There are no signs of
contaminants or psychotropic compounds.

133
00:17:59,720 --> 00:18:03,800
How about you? How are you doing?

134
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:06,480
Depression.

135
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:11,320
Along with bouts of hypomania
and primary insomnia.

136
00:18:11,560 --> 00:18:15,200
Suggestions of agoraphobia,
obsessive-compulsive disorder,

137
00:18:15,440 --> 00:18:17,480
shock, fatigue, denial...

138
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:21,440
- Not unusual, given the circumstances.
- I know.

139
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:27,560
All right. Now, what can you tell me
about what's happening here?

140
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:33,080
Just that I want it to stop,
but I want to stop it.

141
00:18:33,320 --> 00:18:38,600
If I can stop it that means
I'm smarter than it is.

142
00:18:43,440 --> 00:18:48,520
You know you can go home,
walk away from all of this.

143
00:18:48,760 --> 00:18:52,640
I can guarantee it.

144
00:18:57,800 --> 00:19:00,080
Yeah.

145
00:19:00,320 --> 00:19:06,040
The thing is... Man, I would kill
to go back there. I'd... kill.

146
00:19:06,280 --> 00:19:08,720
But Gordon?

147
00:19:08,960 --> 00:19:13,640
Gordon happens to be Gordon, you know?

148
00:19:13,840 --> 00:19:17,320
So, um...

149
00:19:20,960 --> 00:19:24,360
But I'll see what I can do.

150
00:19:24,600 --> 00:19:28,880
<i>We take off into the cosmos.</i>

151
00:19:29,240 --> 00:19:34,240
<i>Ready for anything -
solitude, hardship, exhaustion...</i>

152
00:19:34,480 --> 00:19:37,560
<i>death.</i>

153
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:40,720
<i>We're proud of ourselves.</i>

154
00:19:40,960 --> 00:19:46,440
<i>But when you think about it,
our enthusiasm's a sham.</i>

155
00:19:49,160 --> 00:19:54,240
<i>We don't want other worlds. We want mirrors.</i>

156
00:22:35,240 --> 00:22:38,040
So, anyway... How's the spawn?

157
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:41,680
Oh, good, good. He cries
and shits in his pants every two hours.

158
00:22:41,920 --> 00:22:45,400
I know the feeling.

159
00:22:45,640 --> 00:22:47,520
When are you leaving?

160
00:22:47,760 --> 00:22:51,280
- We've been postponed again.
- I didn't hear that.

161
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:53,160
Nobody knows yet.

162
00:22:53,400 --> 00:22:57,600
The governments are looking for a buyer. I
wish we could tell people what's happening.

163
00:22:57,840 --> 00:22:59,960
You can tell me. I'm a doctor.

164
00:23:00,200 --> 00:23:04,000
Well, Doctor, as we study Solaris,

165
00:23:04,240 --> 00:23:08,200
the most interesting thing is it, um...

166
00:23:08,440 --> 00:23:12,960
Well, it seems to be reacting.
Almost like it knows it's being observed.

167
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:15,760
We can't explain it.

168
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:19,600
Are you listening to me? Chris?

169
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:24,880
- So anyway...
- So anyway. Sorry.

170
00:23:25,120 --> 00:23:31,080
Go to her. Her name is Rheya. She's a bit
tricky but, um, I guess she's worthwhile.

171
00:23:31,320 --> 00:23:33,280
Maybe she needs a shrink.

172
00:23:33,520 --> 00:23:36,920
Don't we all?

173
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:23,600
Don't blow it.

174
00:24:27,400 --> 00:24:28,960
<i>You start.</i>

175
00:24:29,200 --> 00:24:31,200
<i>I did.</i>

176
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:33,000
<i>Really?</i>

177
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:39,320
All right, I'm gonna resist the impulse
to ask you about the door knob.

178
00:24:39,440 --> 00:24:42,720
- Do you always resist your impulses?
- Not always.

179
00:24:44,560 --> 00:24:48,440
<i>Try poetry.</i>

180
00:24:48,800 --> 00:24:51,640
<i>"And death shall have no dominion."</i>

181
00:24:51,880 --> 00:24:55,480
<i>Mm. Thomas.</i>

182
00:24:55,720 --> 00:25:00,000
<i>It's not a very happy poem, though.</i>

183
00:25:00,080 --> 00:25:06,560
<i>Well, you didn't seem
very happy when I saw you on the train.</i>

184
00:25:09,640 --> 00:25:11,960
<i>I wasn't.</i>

185
00:25:12,200 --> 00:25:15,680
<i>And tonight?</i>

186
00:25:16,680 --> 00:25:20,320
<i>It's early.</i>

187
00:27:55,800 --> 00:27:59,280
Goddammit!

188
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:34,760
I'm awake.

189
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:38,280
Yes.

190
00:28:38,560 --> 00:28:40,600
How are you here?

191
00:28:40,840 --> 00:28:42,880
How are you here?

192
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:46,480
How do you mean?

193
00:28:46,720 --> 00:28:53,240
Where do you think you are?
Where do you think you are right now?

194
00:28:53,600 --> 00:28:56,720
At home.

195
00:28:56,960 --> 00:29:00,840
Where is home?

196
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:04,280
With you, where we live.

197
00:29:04,520 --> 00:29:11,400
And do you remember being anywhere else
with me? Being together anywhere else?

198
00:29:12,640 --> 00:29:17,120
- Our apartment.
- Describe it.

199
00:29:17,760 --> 00:29:22,040
It's dark. It's very very dark.

200
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:27,200
And there are no paintings on the wall.

201
00:29:27,440 --> 00:29:30,720
No pictures anywhere.

202
00:29:30,960 --> 00:29:36,400
No pictures on the fridge, even,
which I always thought was a bit strange.

203
00:29:36,640 --> 00:29:41,880
Do you remember
where we first saw each other?

204
00:29:42,920 --> 00:29:46,600
On a train.

205
00:29:54,680 --> 00:29:57,760
Chris...

206
00:30:03,640 --> 00:30:07,600
I'm so happy to see you.

207
00:30:08,360 --> 00:30:12,280
I love you so much.

208
00:30:16,680 --> 00:30:20,960
Don't you love me any more?

209
00:30:24,120 --> 00:30:27,320
I have to check out something with the crew.

210
00:30:27,560 --> 00:30:29,120
No! No!

211
00:30:29,360 --> 00:30:34,320
- Don't leave me! Don't leave me!
- Why? Why?

212
00:30:35,360 --> 00:30:39,040
- Why?
- I don't know.

213
00:30:40,520 --> 00:30:44,000
I don't know.

214
00:30:46,120 --> 00:30:47,920
It's OK.

215
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:51,640
It's OK.

216
00:30:59,800 --> 00:31:03,760
Why are you sitting over there?

217
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:11,320
Can I come and sit with you?

218
00:32:26,840 --> 00:32:30,120
Hey.

219
00:32:32,920 --> 00:32:37,000
What was that?

220
00:32:38,720 --> 00:32:40,440
Yeah.

221
00:32:40,680 --> 00:32:43,880
How 'bout that?

222
00:32:44,120 --> 00:32:47,920
Still workin' on that.

223
00:32:50,720 --> 00:32:53,360
Where's your visitor?

224
00:32:53,600 --> 00:32:58,080
I don't know. Stopped appearing.

225
00:32:58,800 --> 00:33:03,080
- Who's your visitor?
- My brother.

226
00:33:21,160 --> 00:33:24,480
Who was it?

227
00:33:24,720 --> 00:33:28,200
My wife.

228
00:33:29,080 --> 00:33:32,160
Dead?

229
00:33:39,200 --> 00:33:43,160
So what was her name?

230
00:33:43,800 --> 00:33:47,760
Will she come back?

231
00:33:52,920 --> 00:33:56,560
Do you want her to?

232
00:34:52,120 --> 00:34:53,840
- No, it isn't.
- Yes, it is.

233
00:34:54,080 --> 00:34:57,000
- No, it isn't. It's crap.
- Only one way to find out.

234
00:34:57,240 --> 00:35:00,400
You can submit it to someone
and see if they publish it.

235
00:35:00,640 --> 00:35:02,840
That's not an indication of anything.

236
00:35:03,080 --> 00:35:07,600
So no one else's opinion counts
except for yours?

237
00:35:07,840 --> 00:35:11,080
- Yeah.
- That's insane.

238
00:35:11,320 --> 00:35:13,520
- "That's" insane.
- I like it.

239
00:35:13,760 --> 00:35:18,040
Brings out the red in my eyes.

240
00:35:20,480 --> 00:35:23,520
So, did you show it to your father?

241
00:35:23,760 --> 00:35:25,400
- Yeah.
- And?

242
00:35:25,640 --> 00:35:28,000
- And he liked it.
- What'd he say?

243
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:32,200
- He said he liked it.
- Well...

244
00:35:32,600 --> 00:35:38,040
He's a man who doesn't pass out
compliments very easily. That's something.

245
00:35:38,280 --> 00:35:41,800
- What's that tell you?
- Can we talk about something else? Please?

246
00:35:42,040 --> 00:35:46,320
All right. When do you wanna get hitched?

247
00:35:48,760 --> 00:35:53,480
Every time I bring it up
you make a joke about it, and...

248
00:35:53,720 --> 00:35:57,800
I know, I know. That's pathet...
I'm sorry. It's just...

249
00:35:58,040 --> 00:35:59,920
It-it's so difficult for me.

